I11(12) The term ``State'' means a State of the United States, the District of Columbia, the Commonwealth of Puerto Rico, or a territory or possession of the United States.

I11(13) The term ``identification'' means_

I12(A) in the case of any individual, the name, the mailing address, and the occupation of such individual, as well as the name of his or her employer; and

I12(B) in the case of any other person, the full name and address of such person.

Q04

I11(14) The term ``national committee'' means the organization which, by virtue of the bylaws of a political party, is responsible for the day-to-day operation of such political party at the national level, as determined by the Commission.

I11(15) The term ``State committee'' means the organization which, by virtue of the bylaws of a political party, is responsible for the day-to-day operation of such political party at the State level, as determined by the Commission.

I11(16) The term ``political party'' means an association, committee, or organization which nominates a candidate for election to any Federal office whose name appears on the election ballot as the candidate of such association, committee, or organization.

I11(17) T4Independent expenditureK._The term ``independent expenditure'' means an expenditure by a person_

I12(A) expressly advocating the election or defeat of a clearly identified candidate; and

I12(B) that is not made in concert or cooperation with or at the request or suggestion of such candidate, the candidate's authorized political committee, or their agents, or a political party committee or its agents.

Q04

I11(18) The term ``clearly identified'' means that_

I12(A) the name of the candidate involved appears;

I12(B) a photograph or drawing of the candidate appears; or

I12(C) the identity of the candidate is apparent by unambiguous reference.

Q04

I11(19) The term ``Act'' means the Federal Election Campaign Act of 1971 as amended.

I11(20) T4Federal election activity._

I12(A) T4In generalK._The term ``Federal election activity'' means_

I13(i) voter registration activity during the period that begins on the date that is 120 days before the date a regularly scheduled Federal election is held and ends on the date of the election;

I13(ii) voter identification, get-out-the-vote activity, or generic campaign activity conducted in connection with an election in which a candidate for Federal office appears on the ballot (regardless of whether a candidate for State or local office also appears on the ballot);

I13(iii) a public communication that refers to a clearly identified candidate for Federal office (regardless of whether a candidate for State or local office is also mentioned or identified) and that promotes or supports a candidate for that office, or attacks or opposes a candidate for that office (regardless of whether the communication expressly advocates a vote for or against a candidate); or

I13(iv) services provided during any month by an employee of a State, district, or local committee of a political party who spends more than 25 percent of that individual's compensated time during that month on activities in connection with a Federal election.

Q04

I12(B) T4Excluded activityK._The term ``Federal election activity'' does not include an amount expended or disbursed by a State, district, or local committee of a political party for_

I13(i) a public communication that refers solely to a clearly identified candidate for State or local office, if the communication is not a Federal election activity described in subparagraph (A)(i) or (ii);

I13(ii) a contribution to a candidate for State or local office, provided the contribution is not designated to pay for a Federal election activity described in subparagraph (A);

I13(iii) the costs of a State, district, or local political convention; and

I13(iv) the costs of grassroots campaign materials, including buttons, bumper stickers, and yard signs, that name or depict only a candidate for State or local office.

Q04

I11(21) T4Generic campaign activityK._The term ``generic campaign activity'' means a campaign activity that promotes a political party and does not promote a candidate or non-Federal candidate.

I11(22) T4Public communicationK._The term ``public communication'' means a communication by means of any broadcast, cable, or satellite communication, newspaper, magazine, outdoor advertising facility, mass mailing, or telephone bank to the general public, or any other form of general public political advertising.

I11(23) T4Mass mailingK._The term ``mass mailing'' means a mailing by United States mail or facsimile of more than 500 pieces of mail matter of an identical or substantially similar nature within any 30-day period.

I11(24) T4Telephone bankK._The term ``telephone bank'' means more than 500 telephone calls of an identical or substantially similar nature within any 30-day period.

I11(25) T4Election cycleK._For purposes of sections 441a(i) and 441aÿ091 of this title and paragraph (26), the term ``election cycle'' means the period beginning on the day after the date of the most recent election for the specific office or seat that a candidate is seeking and ending on the date of the next election for that office or seat. For purposes of the preceding sentence, a primary election and a general election shall be considered to be separate elections.

I11(26) T4Personal fundsK._The term ``personal funds'' means an amount that is derived from_

I12(A) any asset that, under applicable State law, at the time the individual became a candidate, the candidate had legal right of access to or control over, and with respect to which the candidate had_

I13(i) legal and rightful title; or

I13(ii) an equitable interest;

Q04

I12(B) income received during the current election cycle of the candidate, including_

I13(i) a salary and other earned income from bona fide employment;

I13(ii) dividends and proceeds from the sale of the candidate's stocks or other investments;

I13(iii) bequests to the candidate;

I13(iv) income from trusts established before the beginning of the election cycle;

I13(v) income from trusts established by bequest after the beginning of the election cycle of which the candidate is the beneficiary;

I13(vi) gifts of a personal nature that had been customarily received by the candidate prior to the beginning of the election cycle; and

I13(vii) proceeds from lotteries and similar legal games of chance; and

Q04

I12(C) a portion of assets that are jointly owned by the candidate and the candidate's spouse equal to the candidate's share of the asset under the instrument of conveyance or ownership, but if no specific share is indicated by an instrument of conveyance or ownership, the value of \1/2\ of the property.

