I89. Open World Leadership Center

I19(a) Establishment

I79(1) In general

I12There is established in the legislative branch of the Government a center to be known as the ``Open World Leadership Centerÿ1A\1\N (the ``Center'').

I28N\1\ÿ1ASo in original. Probably should be followed by closing quotation marks.

I79(2) Board of Trustees

I12The Center shall be subject to the supervision and direction of a Board of Trustees (the ``Board'') which shall be composed of 11 members as follows:

I13(A) Two Members of the House of Representatives appointed by the Speaker of the House of Representatives, one of whom shall be designated by the Majority Leader of the House of Representatives and one of whom shall be designated by the Minority Leader of the House of Representatives.

I13(B) Two Senators appointed by the President pro tempore of the Senate, one of whom shall be designated by the Majority Leader of the Senate and one of whom shall be designated by the Minority Leader of the Senate.

I13(C) The Librarian of Congress.

I13(D) Four private individuals with interests in improving relations between the United States and eligible foreign states, designated by the Librarian of Congress.

I13(E) The chair of the Subcommittee on Legislative Branch of the Committee on Appropriations of the House of Representatives and the chair of the Subcommittee on Legislative Branch of the Committee on Appropriations of the Senate.

Q04

I17Each member appointed under this paragraph shall serve for a term of 3 years. Any vacancy shall be filled in the same manner as the original appointment and the individual so appointed shall serve for the remainder of the term. Members of the Board shall serve without pay, but shall be entitled to reimbursement for travel, subsistence, and other necessary expenses incurred in the performance of their duties.

I19(b) Purpose and authority of the Center

I79(1) Purpose

I12The purpose of the Center is to establish, in accordance with the provisions of paragraph (2), a program to enable emerging political leaders of eligible foreign states at all levels of government to gain significant, firsthand exposure to the American free market economic system and the operation of American democratic institutions through visits to governments and communities at comparable levels in the United States and to establish and administer a program to enable cultural leaders of Russia to gain significant, firsthand exposure to the operation of American cultural institutions.

I79(2) Grant program

I12Subject to the provisions of paragraphs (3) and (4), the Center shall establish a program under which the Center annually awards grants to government or community organizations in the United States that seek to establish programs under which those organizations will host nationals of eligible foreign states who are emerging political leaders at any level of government.

I79(3) Restrictions

I18(A) Duration

I13The period of stay in the United States for any individual supported with grant funds under the program shall not exceed 30 days.

I18(B) Limitation

I13The number of individuals supported with grant funds under the program shall not exceed 3,500 in any fiscal year.

I18(C) Use of funds

I13Grant funds under the program shall be used to pay_

I14(i) the costs and expenses incurred by each program participant in traveling between an eligible foreign state and the United States and in traveling within the United States;

I14(ii) the costs of providing lodging in the United States to each program participant, whether in public accommodations or in private homes; and

I14(iii) such additional administrative expenses incurred by organizations in carrying out the program as the Center may prescribe.

I79(4) Application

I18(A) In general

I13Each organization in the United States desiring a grant under this section shall submit an application to the Center at such time, in such manner, and accompanied by such information as the Center may reasonably require.

I18(B) Contents

I13Each application submitted pursuant to subparagraph (A) shall_

I14(i) describe the activities for which assistance under this section is sought;

I14(ii) include the number of program participants to be supported;

I14(iii) describe the qualifications of the individuals who will be participating in the program; and

I14(iv) provide such additional assurances as the Center determines to be essential to ensure compliance with the requirements of this section.

I19(c) Establishment of Fund

I79(1) In general

I12There is established in the Treasury of the United States a trust fund to be known as the ``Open World Leadership Center Trust Fund'' (the ``Fund'') which shall consist of amounts which may be appropriated, credited, or transferred to it under this section.

I79(2) Donations

I12Any money or other property donated, bequeathed, or devised to the Center under the authority of this section shall be credited to the Fund.

I79(3) Fund management

I18(A) In general

I13The provisions of subsections (b), (c), and (d) of section 1105 of this title, and the provisions of section 1106(b) of this title, shall apply to the Fund.

I18(B) Expenditures

I13The Secretary of the Treasury is authorized to pay to the Center from amounts in the Fund such sums as the Board determines are necessary and appropriate to enable the Center to carry out the provisions of this section.

I19(d) Executive Director

I11On behalf of the Board, the Librarian of Congress shall appoint an Executive Director who shall be the chief executive officer of the Center and who shall carry out the functions of the Center subject to the supervision and direction of the Board of Trustees. The Executive Director of the Center shall be compensated at the annual rate specified by the Board, but in no event shall such rate exceed level III of the Executive Schedule under section 5314 of title 5.

I19(e) Administrative provisions

I79(1) In general

I12The provisions of section 1108 of this title shall apply to the Center.

I79(2) Support provided by Library of Congress

I12The Library of Congress may disburse funds appropriated to the Center, compute and disburse the basic pay for all personnel of the Center, provide administrative, legal, financial management, and other appropriate services to the Center, and collect from the Fund the full costs of providing services under this paragraph, as provided under an agreement for services ordered under sections 1535 and 1536 of title 31.

I19(f) Authorization of appropriations

